---
/** Personal finance: college degree ROI. */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import CollegeRoiCalculator from '../../components/calculators/CollegeRoiCalculator.tsx';
import { collegeROI } from '../../lib/personal-finance';
import { formatMoney, formatPct } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = collegeROI({ degreeCost: 100000, yearsToComplete: 4, startingSalary: 65000, salaryGrowth: 0.03, altPathCost: 5000, altStartingSalary: 40000, careerYears: 40 });
---

<Base
  title="College degree ROI calculator 2026"
  description="Is the degree worth it? Compare lifetime earnings with a degree against a trade school or going straight to work, counting the cost and the later start."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">Personal finance</p>
    <h1>College degree ROI</h1>
    <p class="tagline">A degree costs money and four years of earning. Does the higher salary make it back? This weighs the two paths over a whole career.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    A degree is an investment: you pay tuition and give up several years of income, in exchange for a higher salary
    that compounds over a career. Whether that pays off depends on the cost, the salary gap, and how long you work.
    This compares the degree path against an alternative — trade school, or straight to work.
  </p>

  <CollegeRoiCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>A {formatMoney(100000)} degree (4 years) starting at {formatMoney(65000)}, versus a {formatMoney(5000)} path starting at {formatMoney(40000)}:</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Measure</th><th>Value</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Lifetime earnings with the degree</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.degreeLifetime)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lifetime earnings, alternative path</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.altLifetime)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Net lifetime gain from the degree</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.netGain)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Return on the degree's cost</td><td>{formatPct(ex.roi)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Break-even year</td><td>{ex.breakEvenYear ? `year ${ex.breakEvenYear}` : 'not within a career'}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The degree nets {formatMoney(ex.netGain)} more over a 40-year career — a {formatPct(ex.roi)} return on its
    {' '}{formatMoney(100000)} cost — but only pulls ahead of the alternative in year {ex.breakEvenYear}. The early
    years favor the person who skipped the cost and started earning; the degree wins on the long compounding of a
    higher salary.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does this prove college is or isn't worth it?</h3>
    <p>No — it prices one specific comparison you enter. A cheap in-state degree into a high-paying field looks very
      different from an expensive degree into a low-paying one. Change the inputs and the answer changes; that's the
      point.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What about the risk of not finishing?</h3>
    <p>It's real and not modeled. Roughly a third of students don't finish within six years, and a partial degree
      carries much of the cost with little of the salary gain. Weigh completion odds alongside the dollar figure.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Isn't there value beyond money?</h3>
    <p>Yes — this measures earnings only. The non-financial value of an education, a professional network, or work
      you find meaningful doesn't show up in the number and can be decisive.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/college-savings-gap-calculator/">College savings gap</a> — are you saving enough for it?</li>
    <li><a href="/cost-of-procrastinating-investing-calculator/">Cost of waiting to invest</a> — the compounding idea, applied to money</li>
    <li><a href="/net-worth-calculator/">Net worth</a> — where the earnings gap lands</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">Weighs earnings only, on stated assumptions. Not financial advice.</p>
</Base>
